Errol Walton Barrow and the postwar transformation of Barbados :
Includes bibliographical references, bibliography and index.

"Beginning in the 1920s, Barbadians and other British West Indians began organizing politically in an international environment that was marked by a severe capitalist economic and financial crisis that intensified in the 1930s. The response in the British Caribbean during the 1930s was in the form of rebellions that demanded colonial reform. The ensuing struggles resulted in constitutional and political changes that led to decolonization and independence Watson situates the role Errol Barrow played in the transformation of Barbados in the wider Caribbean and international context. His study draws on archival records from Britain and Barbados, interviews and other sources, and he pays close attention to how the racialization of social life around nature, culture, history, the state, class, gender, politics, poverty and other factors conditioned the colonial experience".
theological reflections by Neville W. deSouza on Jamaica's journey, 1979-2000 /

"The project of decolonisation in the Caribbean is an ongoing one. The emergence of Caribbean theological reflection and the development of Caribbean Theology has naturally been part and parcel of the growing consciousness of Caribbean identity that began in the 1960s. Initially stymied by influences from the North that wrongly identified the movement as Liberation Theology with the attendant tentacles of socialism, Neville W. deSouza was the outspoken 12th Bishop of the Diocese of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands whose expressions of the role of the church and the state and the alignment of the church with the working class, the people, rather than elite, to bring about social change, gave voice to the indigenization of the Church in Jamaica. In Journey to the Promised Land, Howard K.A. Gregory presents deSouza's Synod sermons between 1980 and 2000. Delivered during a socially and economically tumultuous time in Jamaica's contemporary history, deSouza brought theological and biblical reflection on the challenges facing the country and the mission to which the Church and the nation were called. Two decades later, the messages still resonate and reflect the depth of Bishop deSouza's theological reflection".

Well-documented study on the foreign policy during the two terms of Haitian President René Préval. Préval (1943) was twice President of the Republic of Haiti (1996-2001 and 2006-2011). Préval was president when the 2010 earthquake hit Haiti.

parcours tumultueux d'un militant, un biographie non autorisée /

Unauthorized biography of Evans Paul (1955), also known as Compère Plume (or K-Plume (KP)), is a Haitian politician and former president of the Democratic United Committee. He was elected mayor of Port-au-Prince in 1990 the same year that Jean-Bertrand Aristide's National Front for Change and Democracy party came to power. He made an unsuccessful run for President of Haiti in the 2006 elections under the Democratic Alliance Party banner. He was leader of the Convergence Démocratique prior to the 2004 Haitian coup d'état which overthrew Aristide. On December 25, 2014, President Michel Martelly appointed Evans Paul as Haiti's new prime minister. He served as prime minister until 2016. He was also host of the radio program "Plume" on Radio Caraïbes from 1974 to 1976 (where he got his nickname).
Glynne Manley ; with a foreward by Jeremy Corbyn and an afterword by Anthony Bogue.

"Michael Manley is perhaps the most written about and the best-chronicled leader of any Caribbean nation of the modern era. Yet none of the three published biographies or the numerous articles and analyses of his legacy as Jamaica's most controversial leader has succeeded in taking readers beyond his public persona to reveal who Michael Manley really was - until now - and in his own words. Truth be Told is not Michael Manley's autobiography, but it is as close to one the world will ever get. Rather, it is the transcribed text of three years of taped interviews conducted by his wife Glynne between 1993 and 1996. Manley passed in 1997".

Study of the immigrant situation in the Dominican Republic and its threat to the nation. Manuel Núñez is considered one of the most polemic essayists in the Dominican Republic. In 1990 he was awarded the National Essay Prize for his work on Dominican national identity, El ocaso de la nación dominicana.

Bruno Rosario Candelier (1941) is a well-known Dominican philologist, literary critic, essayist, professor, novelist and one of the most influential Dominican intellectuals, He has published more than 30 titles and is currently the Director of the Academia Dominicana de la Lengua Española. Some of his more recent works include La fragua del sentido (2009), El Logos en la conciencia (2010), La mística en América (2010), Fundamento estético del Interiorismo (2011), El pensamiento creativo (2011), La lírica metafísica (2011), La aventura visionaria (2011), La belleza y el sentido (2012), Interiorismo del Bruno Rosario Candelier (2015), La Conciencia del lenguaje : estudios y ensayos lingüísticos (2015) and Diccionario fraseológico del español dominicano (2016).

Reference book with biographical information on the presidents the Dominican Republic from 1844 to 2018. The entries are written by a group of 13 Dominican historians such as Carlos Esteban Deive, Jorge Tena Reyes, Vetilio Alfau Duran, Manuel Nuñez, Andrés Blanco Díaz, among others.
Alfonso Reyes y Pedro Henríguez Ureña en Argentina /

Well-documented study on the cultural, intellectual and literary contributions of Pedro Henriquez Ureña (1884-1946) and Alfonso Reyes (1889-1959) during their time in Argentina. Pedro Henríquez Ureña (1884-1946), the great Dominican humanist, is considered one of the most important scholars of the Spanish language, son of the Dominican poet Salomé Ureña and Francisco Henríquez y Carvajal, Dominican doctor, lawyer, writer and educator. Henríquez Ureña published Horas de estudio (1910), En la orilla de mi España (1922), La utopía de América (1925), Seis ensayos en busca de nuestra expresión (1928), La cultura y las letras coloniales de Santo Domingo (1936), y Corrientes literarias en la América Hispana (1941), among many other works. Alfonso Reyes Ochoa (1889-1959) was a Mexican writer, philosopher and diplomat. He was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature five times.

Puerto Rico, una mirada en tiempos revueltos /

Compilation of newspapers columns originally published in El Nuevo Día (Puerto Rico's most important daily newspaper) from 2005-2017. The Puerto Rican themes include the financial crisis, human rights, political corruption, the health crisis, the statehood movement, censure, and daily life, among others. The author is a lawyer and legal scholar who has published Principios y técnicas de la practica forense (1999), Alegación preacordada en los Estados Unidos (2009, awarded First Prize, Premio Federación Interamericana de Abogados) and El proceso penal de Puerto Rico (2009, Premio Obra Judicial del Año, Colegio de Abogados de Puerto Rico).
apuntes biográficos desde la distancia aguadillana /

Biography of Rafael Hernández (1891-1965), Puerto Rican composer and one of Latin America's most important and prolific popular music composers. Hernández is author of hundreds of songs in the Latin American repertoire such as Lamento Borincano, considered the first protest song to be recorded in Latin America, El cumbanchero, Ausencia, Perfume de gardenia, Silencio, and Preciosa, among others. This biography traces his early years in the coastal town of Aguadilla, soldier in War World I in France, his years in New York, his musically productive years in Mexico, and finally his return to his native Puerto Rico.
